{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9b3141d0-abbe-41a7-9dc0-ba9d88072ab3","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you can use the modern patterns:\n\n### Recommended approach\n\n**Constructor injection** for `TestContext` + sync init, and **`[TestInitialize]`** returning `Task` for async init:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    // Constructor: sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n    }\n\n    // Async init runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/warmup\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public void Cleanup() => _client.Dispose();\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void Test1()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Key points for MSTest 3.x\n\n| Pattern | Use |\n|---|---|\n| **Constructor(`TestContext`)** | Sync init + context injection |\n| **`[TestInitialize] async Task`** | Async per-test setup |\n| **`[ClassInitialize]`** | One-time class-level setup |\n| **`IAsyncDisposable`** | Alternative to `[TestCleanup]` for async teardown |\n\nThe old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern still works but constructor injection is preferred in v3.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"83fc4d9f-584c-48ba-8875-cdff40b8539b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended approach has changed significantly:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest 3.x, you can inject `TestContext` via constructor injection rather than the old property-based approach.\n\n2. **Initialization**: MSTest 3.x supports:\n   - Constructor for sync init\n   - `IAsyncInitialization` interface... actually no, that's not MSTest.\n   - `[TestInitialize]` for sync per-test init\n   - `[TestInitialize]` can also be async (returning Task)\n   - `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` for class-level setup and teardown, both supporting async\n   - `IDisposable` and `IAsyncDisposable` for resource cleanup\n\nSo the modern MSTest 3.x patterns give you multiple options depending on whether you need per-test or class-level initialization, and whether you're dealing with sync or async operations.","outputTokens":797,"requestId":"67D3:226394:2C4ED61:30F3DAA:69FD3F25"},"id":"9d564c4a-e0a2-4817-bdbb-75959883c87f","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:41:08.408Z","parentId":"ae33a2f5-78e8-4f86-8b32-4915aab5afa0"}
